[
    {
        "content": "<p>For which toposes is the category of its points small?</p>",
        "id": 251073078,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1630174785
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of points of a localic topos is always (essentially) small.  Beyond that I don't know a general answer; e.g. I wouldn't expect there to be any clean criterion for which geometric theories have only a small number of isomorphism classes of models in Set.</p>",
        "id": 251095440,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1630199995
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you very much!</p>",
        "id": 251124875,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1630234861
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My motivation for the question was that I wanted to find a left inverse of the inclusion of sober spaces into toposes. My idea was to send a topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> to the the space given by the points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> and the open subtoposes of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>. But since the points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> need not form a set, this isn't well-defined.<br>\nSo is it the cases that the inclusion of sober spaces into toposes does not have a left inverse?<br>\nBut how, then, would one categorically express that a sober space can be <em>reconstructed</em> from its topos of sheaves by considering its points? (Of course one can say that the inclusion is fully faithful, but having something like a left inverse would be slightly better.)<br>\nAlso, does the inclusion of sober spaces into locales have a left inverse?<br>\n(By \"inverse\", I always mean \"inverse up to natural isomorphism\".)</p>",
        "id": 251126340,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1630236522
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>_If_ you have a topos that comes from a sober space then you can perform the reconstruction you suggest.</p>",
        "id": 251126549,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1630236781
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, I don't know if the assignment <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo>↦</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>points of </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mtext>, subtoposes of </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E\\mapsto (\\text{points of }\\mathcal E\\text{, subtoposes of }\\mathcal E)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69433em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">points of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">, subtoposes of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is functorial, i.e., induces a continuous map for each topos morphism. Is it?</p>",
        "id": 251126618,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1630236853
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, it is functorial, because you can pull back open subtoposes.</p>",
        "id": 251129350,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1630239963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Any topos has a \"localic reflection\", obtained from the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/%28hyperconnected%2C+localic%29+factorization+system\">hyperconnected-localic</a> factorization system.  Thus, the inclusion of locales in toposes has a left inverse which is in fact a left adjoint.  Similarly, the inclusion of sober spaces in locales has a left inverse that is a right adjoint, which takes the space of points.  So combined, the inclusion of sober spaces in toposes also has a left inverse, though it is no longer an adjoint on either side.</p>",
        "id": 251136895,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1630248131
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> Cool! How does this particular left inverse of the inclusion of sober spaces in toposes differ from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo>↦</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>points of </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mtext>, subtoposes of </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E\\mapsto (\\text{points of }\\mathcal E\\text{, subtoposes of }\\mathcal E)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69433em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">points of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">, subtoposes of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 251464486,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1630445835
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know offhand, sorry.</p>",
        "id": 251468566,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1630447866
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, for one thing, taking the localic reflection first ensures that you get a small set of points.</p>",
        "id": 251473068,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1630450438
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"408864\">@Leopold Schlicht</span>, something close to<br>\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo>↦</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>points of </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mtext>, open subtoposes of </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E\\mapsto (\\text{points of }\\mathcal E\\text{, open subtoposes of }\\mathcal E)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69433em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">points of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">, open subtoposes of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span><br>\nis described in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1103.3493\">this</a> paper by Caramello, Section 2.1.</p>\n<p>If you take a set of points <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> of the topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>, then the topology on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> given by the open subtoposes is called the subterminal topology. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a separating set of points, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Sh}(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the localic reflection of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>For a monoid <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>, points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{PSh}(M)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">PSh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> are the same thing as flat left <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>-sets. The topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{PSh}(M)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">PSh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> does not have any open subtoposes (other than the empty topos and the topos itself), so the subterminal topology will be the indiscrete topology. If you then turn this into a sober space, you get just one point.</p>",
        "id": 251525008,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1630486470
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 251566978,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1630506168
    }
